  <section class="card-container">
    <div class="card" style="width: 75rem">
      <div class="card-body">
        <h5 class="card-title text-center">Top 30 Cooking Tips</h5>
        <div class="scrollable-card">
          <ul class="list-group list-group-flush">
            <li class="list-group-item">
              <strong>1.</strong> Always taste as you cook to adjust seasoning.
              <br />
              <em>Reason:</em> Ensures flavors are balanced throughout the
              cooking process.
            </li>
            <li class="list-group-item">
              <strong>2.</strong> Keep your knives sharp for easier and safer
              cutting. <br />
              <em>Reason:</em> Sharp knives require less force, reducing the
              risk of accidents.
            </li>
            <li class="list-group-item">
              <strong>3.</strong> Preheat your pans before adding ingredients.
              <br />
              <em>Reason:</em> Preheating ensures even cooking and prevents
              sticking.
            </li>
            <li class="list-group-item">
              <strong>4.</strong> Read the recipe completely before starting.
              <br />
              <em>Reason:</em> Helps you prepare and avoid missing steps or
              ingredients.
            </li>
            <li class="list-group-item">
              <strong>5.</strong> Use fresh herbs to elevate flavors. <br />
              <em>Reason:</em> Fresh herbs provide more vibrant and aromatic
              flavors.
            </li>
            <li class="list-group-item">
              <strong>6.</strong> Don't overcrowd the pan; it affects cooking
              evenly. <br />
              <em>Reason:</em> Overcrowding lowers the pan's temperature,
              leading to steaming instead of searing.
            </li>
            <li class="list-group-item">
              <strong>7.</strong> Let meat rest after cooking to retain juices.
              <br />
              <em>Reason:</em> Resting allows juices to redistribute, keeping
              the meat tender.
            </li>
            <li class="list-group-item">
              <strong>8.</strong> Use a kitchen scale for precise measurements.
              <br />
              <em>Reason:</em> Improves consistency and accuracy, especially in
              baking.
            </li>
            <li class="list-group-item">
              <strong>9.</strong> Save vegetable scraps to make homemade stock.
              <br />
              <em>Reason:</em> Reduces waste and creates a flavorful base for
              soups and sauces.
            </li>
            <li class="list-group-item">
              <strong>10.</strong> Clean as you go to stay organized. <br />
              <em>Reason:</em> Maintains a tidy workspace and reduces
              post-cooking cleanup.
            </li>
            <li class="list-group-item">
              <strong>11.</strong> Put a bowl of water inside your oven when
              baking to get crispy bread crust. <br />
              <em>Reason:</em> The steam helps create a crusty texture by
              hydrating the dough surface.
            </li>
            <li class="list-group-item">
              <strong>12.</strong> Fry your onions with salt. <br />
              <em>Reason:</em> Salt draws out moisture, helping onions
              caramelize faster.
            </li>
            <li class="list-group-item">
              <strong>13.</strong> Don't cook meat straight from the freezer.
              Allow it to reach room temperature first. <br />
              <em>Reason:</em> Ensures even cooking and prevents overcooking the
              outer layers.
            </li>
            <li class="list-group-item">
              <strong>14.</strong> Brining is key to getting delicious, juicy
              meat. <br />
              <em>Reason:</em> Brining infuses meat with moisture and flavor
              before cooking.
            </li>
            <li class="list-group-item">
              <strong>15.</strong> Add salt continuously while you cook to avoid
              over-salting. <br />
              <em>Reason:</em> Layering salt enhances flavor without
              overpowering.
            </li>
            <li class="list-group-item">
              <strong>16.</strong> Use sugar as a seasoning. <br />
              <em>Reason:</em> Balances acidity and bitterness in savory dishes.
            </li>
            <li class="list-group-item">
              <strong>17.</strong> A little bit of olive oil can add a flavorful
              kick to your dishes. <br />
              <em>Reason:</em> High-quality olive oil enhances the taste of your
              food.
            </li>
            <li class="list-group-item">
              <strong>18.</strong> Don't overcrowd your pan when searing. <br />
              <em>Reason:</em> Allows for proper browning and caramelization.
            </li>
            <li class="list-group-item">
              <strong>19.</strong> Cook your pasta in the sauce at the last
              minute. <br />
              <em>Reason:</em> Infuses pasta with sauce flavor and ensures a
              cohesive dish.
            </li>
            <li class="list-group-item">
              <strong>20.</strong> Skip nonstick pans to get a crispy crust.
              <br />
              <em>Reason:</em> Stainless steel or cast iron pans provide better
              searing.
            </li>
            <li class="list-group-item">
              <strong>21.</strong> Onions are one of the things you add to a pan
              when cooking. <br />
              <em>Reason:</em> Onions form the aromatic base for many dishes.
            </li>
            <li class="list-group-item">
              <strong>22.</strong> Know when to add your herbs. <br />
              <em>Reason:</em> Add hardy herbs early and delicate herbs toward
              the end for the best flavor.
            </li>
            <li class="list-group-item">
              <strong>23.</strong> Toast your spices before using them. <br />
              <em>Reason:</em> Toasting enhances their aroma and flavor.
            </li>
            <li class="list-group-item">
              <strong>24.</strong> Rest dough before baking. <br />
              <em>Reason:</em> Allows gluten to relax and results in better
              texture.
            </li>
            <li class="list-group-item">
              <strong>25.</strong> Always use room temperature ingredients for
              baking. <br />
              <em>Reason:</em> Ensures smoother mixing and even baking.
            </li>
            <li class="list-group-item">
              <strong>26.</strong> Don't flip food too often when grilling.
              <br />
              <em>Reason:</em> Allows for proper browning and grill marks.
            </li>
            <li class="list-group-item">
              <strong>27.</strong> Use a thermometer to check meat doneness.
              <br />
              <em>Reason:</em> Ensures meat is cooked to the correct temperature
              for safety and flavor.
            </li>
            <li class="list-group-item">
              <strong>28.</strong> Chill your mixing bowl when making whipped
              cream. <br />
              <em>Reason:</em> Helps the cream whip faster and stay stable.
            </li>
            <li class="list-group-item">
              <strong>29.</strong> Always dry your ingredients before frying.
              <br />
              <em>Reason:</em> Prevents splattering and ensures crispiness.
            </li>
            <li class="list-group-item">
              <strong>30.</strong> Add acid (like vinegar or lemon juice) to
              balance flavors. <br />
              <em>Reason:</em> Brightens dishes and balances rich or heavy
              flavors.
            </li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

